snippet.textDisplay: I'll agree the Floyd missions were some of the hardest parts of the game. I think it had something to do with the camera perspective. Floyd's mission difficulty didn't ramp properly, but the devs were getting feedback from gamers who put their day into being great at playing a hard game (and a temp like me didn't have suggestions greenlit often). An optional training course would be a nice gesture, though. Thankfully, the controls were pretty tight, which I believe to be part of Rare's pedigree.
snippet.textOriginal: I'll agree the Floyd missions were some of the hardest parts of the game. I think it had something to do with the camera perspective. Floyd's mission difficulty didn't ramp properly, but the devs were getting feedback from gamers who put their day into being great at playing a hard game (and a temp like me didn't have suggestions greenlit often). An optional training course would be a nice gesture, though. Thankfully, the controls were pretty tight, which I believe to be part of Rare's pedigree.

snippet.textDisplay: This was the third game I tested while working at Nintendo, very shortly after completing work on DK64 (I love Rare, so '99 was a good summer for me). Both soundtracks were great, but I preferred JFG for its more challenging single-player gameplay (DK64's multiplayer was better, though). Plenty of variety in the characters' abilities, as well as a good mix of platforming, shooting and a dash of puzzles. I'd like to see a Jet Force Gemini sequel.
snippet.textOriginal: This was the third game I tested while working at Nintendo, very shortly after completing work on DK64 (I love Rare, so '99 was a good summer for me). Both soundtracks were great, but I preferred JFG for its more challenging single-player gameplay (DK64's multiplayer was better, though). Plenty of variety in the characters' abilities, as well as a good mix of platforming, shooting and a dash of puzzles. I'd like to see a Jet Force Gemini sequel.
